# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The **1896 Summer Olympics**, officially known as the **Games of the I Olympiad**, and commonly known as **Athens 1896** (Greek: Αθήνα 1896), were the first international Olympic Games held in modern history.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Organised by the International Olympic Committee (IOC), which had been created by French aristocrat Pierre de Coubertin, the event was held in Athens, Greece, from 6 to 15 April 1896.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Fourteen nations (according to the IOC, though the number is subject to interpretation) and 241 athletes (all males; this number is also disputed) took part in the games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Participants were all European or living in Europe, with the exception of the United States team, and over 65% of the competing athletes were Greek.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Winners were given a silver medal, while runners-up received a copper medal.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Retroactively, the IOC has designated the top three finishers in each event as gold, silver, and bronze medalists.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Ten of the 14 participating nations earned medals.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] On April 6, 1896, American James Connolly became the first Olympic medalist in more than 1,500 years, competing in the triple jump.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The United States won the most gold medals, 11, while host nation Greece won the most medals overall, 47.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The highlight for the Greeks was the marathon victory by their compatriot Spyridon Louis.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The most successful competitor was German wrestler and gymnast Carl Schuhmann, who won four events.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Athens had been chosen to stage the inaugural modern Games during a congress organised by Coubertin in Paris on 23 June 1894, during which the IOC was also created.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The main venue was the Panathenaic Stadium, where athletics and wrestling took place; other venues included the Neo Phaliron Velodrome for cycling and the Zappeion for fencing.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The opening ceremony was held in the Panathenaic Stadium on 6 April, during which most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] After a speech by the president of the organising committee, Crown Prince Constantine, his father officially opened the Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras and written by Kostis Palamas.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The 1896 Olympics were regarded as a great success.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The Games had the largest international participation of any sporting event to that date.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The Panathenaic Stadium overflowed with the largest crowd ever to watch a sporting event.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] After the Games, Coubertin and the IOC were petitioned by several prominent figures, including Greece's King George and some of the American competitors in Athens, to hold all the following Games in Athens.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] However, the 1900 Summer Olympics were already planned for Paris, and, with the exception of the Intercalated Games of 1906, the Olympics did not return to Greece until the 2004 Summer Olympics, 108 years later.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] During the 19th century, several small-scale sports festivals across Europe were named after the ancient Olympic Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The 1870 Olympics at the Panathenaic stadium, which had been refurbished for the occasion, had an audience of 30,000 people.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Pierre de Coubertin, a French pedagogue and historian, adopted William Penny Brookes's idea to establish a multi-national and multi-sport event (even though the ancient games only allowed male athletes of Greek origin to participate).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] In 1890, Coubertin wrote an article in *La Revue Athlétique*, which espoused the importance of Much Wenlock, a rural market town in the English county of Shropshire.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] It was here that, in October 1850, the local physician William Penny Brookes founded the Wenlock Olympian Games, a festival of sports and recreations that included athletics and team sports like cricket, football and quoits.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Coubertin also took inspiration from earlier Greek games organised under the name of Olympics by businessman and philanthropist Evangelis Zappas in 1859, 1870 and 1875.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The 1896 Athens Games were funded by the legacies of Zappas and his cousin Konstantinos Zappas and by George Averoff who had been requested by the Greek government to sponsor the second refurbishment of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The Greek government did this despite the cost of refurbishing the stadium in marble already being funded in full by Evangelis Zappas forty years earlier.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] On 18 June 1894, Coubertin organised a congress at the Sorbonne, Paris, to present his plans to representatives of sports societies from 11 countries.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Following his proposal's acceptance by the congress, a date for the first modern Olympic Games was discussed; Coubertin suggested that the Games be held concurrently with the 1900 Universal Exposition of Paris.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Concerned that a six-year waiting period might lessen public interest, congress members opted to hold the inaugural Games in 1896.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] With a date established, members of the congress discussed the selection of a host city.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] It is unknown how Athens was chosen: Coubertin and Demetrius Vikelas's descriptions of the selection process contradicted the congress's official minutes.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Most accounts state that several congressmen first proposed London, but Coubertin dissented.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] After a brief discussion with Vikelas, who represented Greece, Coubertin suggested Athens.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Vikelas made the Athens proposal official on 23 June; since Greece had been the original home of the Olympics, the congress unanimously approved the decision.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Vikelas was then elected the first president of the newly established International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The return of the Olympic Games to Greece was well-received by the Greek public, media, and royal family.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The Crown Prince conferred their patronage to the games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] However, the country had financial troubles and was in political turmoil.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The country's prime minister frequently alternated between Charilaos Trikoupis and Theodoros Deligiannis during the last years of the 19th century.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] This instability caused Trikoupis and Stephanos Dragoumis, the president of the Zappas Olympic Committee, which had attempted to organise a series of national Olympiads, to believe that Greece could not host the event.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] In late 1894, the organising committee under Stephanos Skouloudis presented a report that the cost of the Games would be three times higher than originally estimated by Coubertin.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] They concluded the Games could not be held and offered their resignation.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] With the prospect of reviving the Olympic games in doubt, Coubertin and Vikelas commenced a campaign to increase the Olympic movement's popularity.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] On 7 January 1895 Vikelas announced that crown prince Constantine would assume the presidency of the organising committee.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] His first responsibility was to raise the funds necessary to host the Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] He relied on the patriotism of the Greek people to motivate them to provide the required finances.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Constantine's enthusiasm increased contributions from the Greek public, raising 330,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,106,157,688 in 2025).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] A special set of postage stamps was commissioned; the sale of which raised 400,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,340,797,197 in 2025).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] At the request of Constantine, businessman George Averoff agreed to pay for the restoration of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] As a tribute to his generosity, a statue of Averoff was constructed and unveiled on 5 April 1896 outside the stadium.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The IOC's first regulation, voted on in 1894, was to allow only amateur athletes to participate in the Olympic Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The various contests were thus held under amateur regulations, except for fencing matches.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The rules and regulations were not uniform, so the Organising Committee chose among the codes of the various national athletic associations.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The jury, the referees and the game director bore the same names as in antiquity (*Ephor*, *Helanodic* and *Alitarc*).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Prince George acted as final referee; according to Coubertin, "his presence gave weight and authority to the decisions of the ephors".
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Women could not compete at the 1896 Summer Olympics because Coubertin felt that their inclusion would be "impractical, uninteresting, unaesthetic and incorrect".
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Seven venues were used for the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Panathenaic Stadium was the main venue, hosting four of the nine sports contested.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The town of Marathon hosted the marathon event and the individual road race events.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Fencing was held at the Zappeion, sport shooting at Kallithea, and tennis at the Athens Lawn Tennis Club.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Swimming was held in the Bay of Zea; it was selected because the organizers of the Games wanted to avoid spending money on constructing a special-purpose swimming venue.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Four of the 1896 venues were reused as competition venues for the 2004 Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The velodrome would be renovated into a football stadium in the 1960s and was known as Karaiskakis Stadium.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] This venue was renovated in 2003 for use as a football venue for the 2004 Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] During the 2004 Games, Panathinaiko Stadium hosted the archery competitions and was the finish line for the athletic marathon event.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The city of Marathon itself served as the starting point for both marathon events during the 2004 Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The Zappeion served as the first home of the organizing committee (ATHOC) for the 2004 Games from 1998 to 1999, and served as the press center for non-accredited media during those Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] On Easter Monday 6 April (25 March according to the Julian calendar used in Greece until 1923) the games of the First Olympiad were officially opened.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The Panathenaic Stadium was filled with between 16,000 and 80,000 spectators, including King George I of Greece, his wife Olga, and other members of the royal family.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras, with words by poet Kostis Palamas.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The first announcements regarding the sporting events to be held featured sports like equestrian and cricket, but these plans were not finalised, and these sports did not make the final program for the Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Football is sometimes listed as having been an exhibition or demonstration sport, although whether a football match actually occurred is disputed.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Rowing and sailing events were cancelled on the planned days of competition: sailing due to a lack of special boats in Greece and no foreign entries, and rowing due to poor weather.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The 1896 Summer Olympics programme featured 9 sports encompassing 10 disciplines and 43 events.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The athletics events had the most international field of any of the sports.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The major highlight was the marathon, held for the first time in international competition.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Spyridon Louis, a previously unrecognised water carrier, won the event to become the only Greek athletics champion and a national hero.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Although Greece had been favoured to win the discus and the shot put, the best Greek athletes finished second to American Robert Garrett in both events.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] No world records were set, as few top international competitors had elected to compete and the curves of the track were very tight, making fast times in the running events virtually impossible.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Thomas Burke of the United States won the 100-meter race in 12.0 seconds and the 400-meter race in 54.2 seconds.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Burke was the only one who used the "crouch start" (putting his knee on soil), confusing the jury.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Chile claims one athlete, Luis Subercaseaux, who competed for the nation at the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Subercaseaux's results are not listed in the official report, though that report typically includes only winners and Subercaseaux won no medals.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] He was entered to compete in the 100m, 400m and 800m events but is usually listed as a no show.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] An appraisal of a photo of series 2 of the 100 meters sprint, performed by facial recognition experts of the Chilean forensic police, concluded that Subercaseaux was one of the participants.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The day after the official marathon, Stamata Revithi ran the 40-kilometer course in 5 hours 30 minutes, finishing outside Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Some authors, who believe that "Melpomene" and Revithi are the same person, attribute to the latter the more favorable time of 4+1⁄2 hours.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] She was denied entry into the official race as the 1896 Olympics excluded women from competition.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The cycling competitions used the rules of the International Cycling Association.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The newly built Neo Phaliron Velodrome hosted the track cycling events.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Only one road event was held, a race from Athens to Marathon and back (87 kilometres).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] In the track events, the best cyclist was Frenchman Paul Masson, who won the one lap time trial, the sprint event, and the 10,000 meters.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] In the 100 kilometres event, Masson entered as a pacemaker for his compatriot Léon Flameng.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Flameng won the event, after a fall and after stopping to wait for his Greek opponent Georgios Kolettis to fix a mechanical problem.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The Austrian fencer Adolf Schmal won the 12-hour race, which was completed by only two cyclists, while the road race event was won by Aristidis Konstantinidis.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The fencing events were held in the Zappeion, which, built with money Evangelis Zappas had given to revive the ancient Olympic Games, had never seen any athletic contests before.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Unlike other sports (in which only amateurs were allowed to take part at the Olympics), professionals were authorised to compete in fencing, though in a separate event.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] These masters professionals were considered gentlemen athletes, just like the amateurs.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Four events were scheduled, but the épée event was cancelled for unknown reasons.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The foil event was won by a Frenchman, Eugène-Henri Gravelotte, who beat his countryman, Henri Callot, in the final.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The other two events were won by Greek fencers: Ioannis Georgiadis won the sabre event, and Leonidas Pyrgos won the masters foil, becoming the first Greek Olympic champion in the modern era.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The gymnastics competition was carried out on the infield of the Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Germany sent an 11-man team, which won five of the eight events, including both team events: in the team event on the horizontal bar, the German team was the only entry.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Three Germans added individual titles: Hermann Weingärtner won the horizontal bar event, Alfred Flatow won the parallel bars, and Carl Schuhmann, who also won the wrestling event, won the vault.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Louis Zutter, a Swiss gymnast, won the pommel horse, while Greeks Ioannis Mitropoulos and Nikolaos Andriakopoulos were victorious in the rings and rope climbing events, respectively.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] A regatta of sailing boats was on the program of the Games of the First Olympiad for 31 March 1896 (Julian calendar).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The event was cancelled: the official English report blamed a lack of specialty boats had not been provided while the German version also cited a lack of foreign competitors.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Rowing races were scheduled for the next day, 1 April 1896 (Julian).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Poor weather caused the event to be postponed to 3 pm and German Berthold Küttner stated that he and Adolf Jäger had lined up for the start of the double sculls, the first event to take place.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The event was further postponed to the next day, but the German team still completed the event in the bad weather: they were presented with the winners medal upon the completion of their row.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The next day, the event was formally cancelled when the weather worsened.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The International Olympic Committee does not recognize Küttner's recollection of the events.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Held at a range at Kallithea, the shooting competition consisted of five events—two using a rifle and three with a pistol.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The first event, the military rifle, was won by Pantelis Karasevdas, the only competitor to hit the target with all of his shots.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The second event, for military pistols, was dominated by two American brothers: John and Sumner Paine.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] They became the first siblings to finish first and second in the same event.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] To avoid embarrassing their hosts, the brothers decided that John would withdraw from the free pistol event.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Sumner Paine won that event, becoming the first relative of an Olympic champion to become Olympic champion himself.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The Paine brothers did not compete in the 25-meter pistol event, as the event judges determined that their weapons were not of the required calibre; Ioannis Phrangoudis won the event.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The final event, the free rifle, could not be completed due to darkness and was finalised the next morning, with Georgios Orphanidis winning the competition.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The swimming competition was held in the open sea because the organizers had refused to spend the money necessary for a specially constructed stadium.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Nearly 20,000 spectators lined the Bay of Zea off the Piraeus coast to watch the events.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The water in the bay was cold, and the competitors suffered during their races.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] There were three open events (men's 100-metre freestyle, men's 500-metre freestyle, and men's 1200 metre freestyle), in addition to a special event open only to Greek sailors, all of which were held on the same day (11 April).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] For Alfréd Hajós of Hungary, this meant he could only compete in two of the events, as they were held too close together, which made it impossible for him to adequately recuperate.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Nevertheless, he won the two events in which he swam, the 100 and 1200 meter freestyle.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Hajós later became one of only two Olympians to win a medal in both the athletic and artistic competitions, when he won a silver medal for architecture in 1924.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The 500-meter freestyle was won by Austrian swimmer Paul Neumann, who defeated his opponents by more than a minute and a half.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Although tennis was already a major sport by the end of the 19th century, none of the top players turned up for the tournament in Athens.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The competition was held at the courts of the Athens Lawn Tennis Club, and the infield of the velodrome used for the cycling events.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] John Pius Boland, who won the event, had been entered in the competition by a fellow-student of his at Oxford; the Greek, Konstantinos Manos.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] As a member of the Athens Lawn Tennis sub-committee, Manos had been trying, with the assistance of Boland, to recruit competitors for the Athens Games from among the sporting circles of Oxford University.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] In the first round, Boland defeated Friedrich Traun, a promising tennis player from Hamburg, who had been eliminated in the 100-meter sprint competition.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Boland and Traun decided to team up for the doubles event, in which they reached the final and defeated their Greek opponents after losing the first set.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The sport of weightlifting was still young in 1896, and the rules differed from those in use today.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Competitions were held outdoors, in the infield of the main stadium, and there were no weight limits.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The first event was similar in style to what is now known as the "clean and jerk".
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Two competitors stood out: Briton Launceston Elliot and Viggo Jensen of Denmark.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Both of them lifted the same weight, but the jury, with Prince George as the chairman, ruled that Jensen had done so in a better style.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The British delegation, unfamiliar with this tie-breaking rule, lodged a protest.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The lifters were eventually allowed to make further attempts, but neither lifter improved, and Jensen was declared the champion.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Elliot got his revenge in the one hand lift event, which was held immediately after the two-handed one.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Jensen had been slightly injured during his last two-handed attempt and was no match for Elliot, who won the competition easily.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The Greek audience was charmed by the British victor, whom they considered very attractive.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] A curious incident occurred during the weightlifting event: a servant was ordered to remove the weights, which appeared to be a difficult task for him.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Prince George came to his assistance; he picked up the weight and threw it a considerable distance with ease, to the delight of the crowd.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] No weight classes existed for the wrestling competition, held in the Panathenaic Stadium, which meant that there would only be one winner among competitors of all sizes.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The rules used were similar to modern Greco-Roman wrestling, although there was no time limit, and not all leg holds were forbidden (in contrast to current rules).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Apart from the two Greek contestants, all the competitors had previously been active in other sports.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Weightlifting champion Launceston Elliot faced gymnastics champion Carl Schuhmann.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The latter won and advanced into the final, where he met Georgios Tsitas, who had previously defeated Stephanos Christopoulos.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Darkness forced the final match to be suspended after 40 minutes; it was continued the following day, when Schuhmann needed only fifteen minutes to finish the bout.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] On the morning of Sunday 12 April (or 31 March, according to the Julian calendar then used in Greece), King George organised a banquet for officials and athletes (even though some competitions had not yet been held).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] During his speech, he made clear that, as far as he was concerned, the Olympics should be held in Athens permanently.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The official closing ceremony was held the following Wednesday after being postponed from Tuesday due to rain.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Again, the royal family attended the ceremony, which was opened by the national anthem of Greece and an ode composed in ancient Greek by George S.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Robertson, a British athlete and scholar.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Afterwards, the king awarded prizes to the winners.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Unlike today, the first-place winners received a silver medal, an olive branch and a diploma, while runners-up received a copper medal, a laurel branch and a diploma.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Third place winners did not receive a prize.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Some winners also received additional prizes.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Spyridon Louis received a cup from Michel Bréal, a friend of Coubertin, who had conceived the marathon event.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Louis then led the medalists on a lap of honour around the stadium, while the Olympic Hymn was played again.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The King then formally announced that the first Olympiad was at an end and left the Stadium, while the band played the Greek national hymn and the crowd cheered.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Like the Greek king, many others supported the idea of holding the next Games in Athens; most of the American competitors signed a letter to the Crown Prince expressing this wish.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Coubertin, however, was heavily opposed to this idea, as he envisioned international rotation as one of the cornerstones of the modern Olympics.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] According to his wish, the next Games were held in Paris, although they would be somewhat overshadowed by the concurrent Universal Exposition.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The concept of national teams was not a major part of the Olympic movement until the Intercalated Games 10 years later, though many sources list the nationality of competitors in 1896 and give medal counts.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] There are significant conflicts with regard to which nations competed.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The International Olympic Committee gives a figure of 14, but does not list them.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Different sources provide differing lists of nations; some exclude countries like Chile and Bulgaria, but the IOC lists competitors from both countries.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Egypt is also sometimes included due to the participation of Dimitrios Kasdaglis; however, the IOC classifies him as a Greek athlete.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Belgium and Russia had entered the names of competitors, but no athletes from these countries competed.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] National Olympic Committees did not yet exist.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] Ten of the fourteen participating nations earned medals, in addition to two medals won by mixed teams (teams made up of athletes from multiple nations).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The IOC has retroactively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to the three best placed athletes in each event to comport with more recent traditions.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] In this regard, five of the bronze medalists at the Games are unknown: two in swimming and three in gymnastics.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1896-olympic-games] The United States won the most gold medals (11), while host nation Greece won the most medals overall (47), as well as the most silver (18) and bronze (19) medals, finishing with one fewer gold medal than the United States.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The **1912 Summer Olympics** (Swedish: *Olympiska sommarspelen 1912*), officially known as the **Games of the V Olympiad** (Swedish: *Den V olympiadens spel*) and commonly known as **Stockholm 1912**, were an international multi-sport event held in Stockholm, Sweden, between 6 July and 22 July 1912.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held on 6 July.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] They were the only Summer Olympics to be held in the 1910s as the 1916 Summer Olympics in Berlin were cancelled due to World War I.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Twenty-eight nations and 2,408 competitors, including 48 women, competed in 102 events in 14 sports.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] With the exception of tennis (starting on 5 May) and football and shooting (both starting on 29 June), the games were held within a month with an official opening on 6 July.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] It was the last Olympics to issue solid gold medals and, with Japan's debut, the first time an official team from an Asian nation participated.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Stockholm was the only bid for the games, and was selected in 1909.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The games were the first to have art competitions, women's diving, women's swimming, and the first to feature both the decathlon and the new pentathlon, both won by the American Jim Thorpe.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Electric timing was introduced in athletics, while the host country disallowed boxing.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Figure skating was rejected by the organizers because they wanted to promote the Nordic Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (26), while hosts Sweden won the most medals overall (65).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] These were the final Olympic Games for eight years due to the disruption of the First World War.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The next Olympic Games were held in 1920 in Antwerp.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Following the 1908 Summer Olympics in London, authorities in Sweden immediately sought to ensure that the next games would be held there.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] There were two Swedish members of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) at the time, Viktor Balck and Clarence von Rosen.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The pair proposed the idea to the Swedish governing bodies of athletics and gymnastics in order to ensure that they backed any potential bid.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Support was given by the national associations on 18 April 1909 for a bid to host the Olympics in Stockholm on the basis that suitable financial arrangements could be made.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] King Gustaf V was petitioned on 6 May 1909 following the publication of preliminary plans for the Stockholm bid that the expected cost of hosting the Games would be 415,000 kronor (£23,050 or $115,250).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Government accepted the petition on behalf of the King and supported the bid.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] On 28 May, at the meeting of the IOC in Berlin, the Swedish representatives declared that they had full financial support for hosting the next Games in Stockholm.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] A deal was made with the German IOC representative on the basis that Berlin would host the 1916 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin spoke at the meeting about his concerns that Sweden should ensure that the Games take place, as he did not want a repeat of the problems with Great Britain hosting the 1908 Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The news that Stockholm was to host the 1912 Olympics was received with enthusiasm by the Swedish public.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The organizing committee took de Coubertin's words to heart, and aimed to achieve an Olympic Games which removed those elements which detracted from earlier Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The committee was elected in the autumn of 1909, with Balck voted as the President of the committee, and Crown Prince Gustaf Adolf selected as Honorary President.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The committee's first meeting took place on 7 October, and on 11 October they delegated the arrangements for the individual branches of sports to the relevant governing bodies in Sweden.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] There were four exceptions to this, with the game shooting, modern pentathlon and mountain ascents retained by the Olympic committee, and the horse riding competitions being organized by Prince Carl, Duke of Västergötland, who was the inspector of the Swedish cavalry.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Altogether there were 187 members of these committees.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The official invitation to compete in the Games was issued on 18 November 1910 to 27 countries, either directly or through their representative on the IOC.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] A further 15 countries were to have been invited, but as they had no IOC representatives, the Swedish authorities were unsure how to proceed.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Once the organizing committee for the Games received confirmation of the athletic associations in each of the 15 countries, they too were sent invitations.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Some 61,800 entry forms were printed for the use of the various nations.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Free transport was arranged for the invited nations' equipment, and a discount of 50 percent was arranged for competitors and delegates on the state run railway.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] A daily newspaper which only covered the Olympics was arranged to be published during the Games, in both English and Swedish.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Further arrangements were made for the general arrival of visitors in order to entertain them whilst they were not at the Games; a pleasure garden was opened north of the Olympic Stadium, and a series of indoor tennis courts were converted into a restaurant.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Twelve sports venues were used in the 1912 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] This marked the first time that more than one venue would be used for the football tournament, which has been the case ever since.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Stockholm Olympic Stadium served as one of the equestrian venues for the 1956 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Råsunda Stadium served as a venue for the 1958 FIFA World Cup and the 1995 FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] In the initial bid document it was identified that a new stadium would be needed, initially envisaged as being located in the Östermalm Athletic Grounds.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] In order to save funds, it was expected that only one of the stadium's stands would be permanent, with the other three made of wood and dismantled following the Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The cost of that stadium was estimated at 235,000 Kronor.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Arrangements were made with the individual national committees to provide the use of Östermalm Athletic Grounds and Traneberg.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The cycling road race was held around Mälaren, the third largest lake in Sweden.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The water events, including the swimming and the rowing, were held at Djurgårdsbrunnsviken, where a stadium was built.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Kaknäs was already used as a shooting range, but alterations were needed to accommodate shooting events.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Although it was not used as the Olympic stadium as originally intended, Östermalm hosted the lawn tennis and fencing competitions after a tennis pavilion was moved there from another location.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Five other locations were considered in addition to the Östermalm Athletic Grounds to locate the Olympic Stadium.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Stockholm Olympic Stadium was built on the site of the former Stockholm Athletic Grounds in order to retain the other locations for other uses during the Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] By placing it to the north of the city, the Olympic Stadium was within the immediate vicinity of other pre-existing sporting venues.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Initial funding was given to the sum of 400,000 Kr for a timber stadium but Torben Grut, the architect, also drew up alternative plans for a stone stadium.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] However it was found that the original estimate for the stone stadium would still be too expensive, and the plans were once more modified in order to simplify the design and reduce costs.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] An agreement was entered into with a contractor on 2 November 1910 that it would be transferred complete by 25 May 1912.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Games of the V Olympiad were opened on 6 July 1912.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish Royal Family left Stockholm Palace at 10:40am, and were received at the Olympic Stadium by members of the IOC.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Three thousand competing athletes had already assembled in the nearby Östermalm Athletic Grounds, and began to enter the stadium in alphabetical order by nation according to the Swedish spelling.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish team entered last, but unlike the later tradition, the Greek team did not enter first.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] A hymn was sung, a traditional Swedish chant was conducted and prayers were read first in Swedish and then in English.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Crown Prince Gustaf Adolf addressed the King on behalf of the Swedish Olympic Association.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Afterwards a trumpet fanfare was played and the Crown Prince called for cheers for the King.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The athletes in their national groups marching out of the stadium in order ended the ceremony.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish delegation at the IOC meeting in Berlin on 28 May 1909 had proposed a simple Olympic schedule containing only "pure" athletics, swimming, gymnastics and wrestling.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] However other countries requested that the schedule be more comprehensive, and with that in mind they put forward a further programme at the IOC meeting in 1911 which was met with approval.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The sports which were added were the tug of war, cycling, fencing, football, horse riding, lawn tennis, rowing, shooting, skating and yacht racing.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The question of adding skating to the programme was discussed once more on 7 February 1910, with the decision being made to drop it from the schedule.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] It was felt to be unsuitable because it was a winter sport, and it was to be part of the Nordic Games the following year.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Boxing was removed from the programme as it was unappealing to the Swedes.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Art competitions were considered at a further meeting on 14 February 1910, and were subsequently added to the programme, but now art competitions are no longer regarded as official Olympic events by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] As a result, now the 1912 Summer Olympics programme considered composed of 14 sports encompassing 18 disciplines and 102 events.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Baseball, Glima (as the second Olympic demonstration of the sport after 1908 Summer Olympics) and Gotland sports were unofficial demonstration sports.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] This was also the first year art competitions were held at the Olympics.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The athletic events saw the introduction of a fully automatic timing system developed by R.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] It involved attaching electromagnets to chronometers in a system which attached a control lamp to the starting gun for each race.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] This resulted in the firing of the gun starting a timer which was then stopped by one of the judges at the finishing line.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The final of the men's 100 metres was expected to be a mostly American affair, and it ended up with six athletes, only one of whom was not from the United States.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] It suffered from seven false starts before the athletes finally got away, with Ralph Craig winning the gold medal by 60 centimetres (24 in) in front of second place Alvah Meyer.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Donald Lippincott won bronze, 15 cm behind the second man.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Shizo Kanakuri, a Japanese marathon runner, went missing during the race.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] He lost consciousness by heatstroke and a farming family helped him to stop at a party taking place in a villa on the marathon route in order to quench his thirst, then caught a train to Stockholm and left the country the next day.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] He returned to Japan without notifying race officials.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Fifty years later, after being invited back by the Swedish authorities, he completed the race with an (unofficial) time of 54 years, 8 months, 6 days, 8 hours, 32 minutes and 20.3 seconds.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Portuguese Francisco Lázaro died from heat exhaustion while running the marathon, the only athlete to die during the running of an Olympic marathon.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] In addition to the physical toll of the event, the reported split time for the 5 km checkpoint at Stocksund (2:17:20 after a 1:48:00 start) implies an unusually slow 29:20 opening segment, followed by an unrealistically fast 10 km pace.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Martin has noted this discrepancy as a likely timing error.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] American Jim Thorpe won the pentathlon and the newly created decathlon.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Thorpe's gold medals were stripped by the International Olympic Committee in 1913, after the IOC learned that Thorpe had taken expense money for playing baseball, violating contemporary Olympic amateurism rules, before the 1912 Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] This moved everyone else up in the rankings.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] In 1982, the IOC was convinced that the disqualification had been improper, as no protest against Thorpe's eligibility had been brought within the required 30 days, and reinstated Thorpe's medals.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The replicas were presented to his children in 1983, 30 years after Thorpe's death.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Finally, in 2022, the IOC posthumously declared Thorpe as the sole winner of the pentathlon and decathlon events after extensive consultations with his former competitors' families who said they had always viewed Thorpe as the winner.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] New Olympic records were set in the majority of track and field events, with only the men's 200 metres, 10 km walk, standing high jump, standing broad jump, hop, step and jump, and the hurdle competitions failing to have new records set.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Tell Berna captured a gold for the 3000m and Henry S.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] "Harry" Babcock took gold for the pole vault, setting an Olympic Record at 3.95m.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Hannes Kolehmainen was the most successful in setting records at the games, with new Olympic Records set in the 5,000, 10,000 metre and cross country races.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The cycling events at the 1912 Games were limited to a road race around Lake Mälaren, which had already been a successful route for a yearly cycling race.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Although not originally in the schedule, several countries requested that track cycling be added; however, the organizing committee stuck by their plans not to build a new track cycling stadium as the only one in Stockholm had been destroyed in order for the Olympic Stadium to be built.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, Germany had specifically requested Cycle-Polo and Figure-Cycling to be added to the programme, both of which requests were turned down by the committee.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] It was decided to hold the road race as a time trial, and to outlaw any non-competitive cyclists acting as pacemakers.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations entered 151 athletes into the competition, which was a greater number than expected by the committee.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The largest group was from Great Britain, who had entered twelve competitors from England, another twelve from Scotland, and a further nine from Ireland.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The race began on 7 July, with the athletes leaving in groups.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The first group left at 2am, with the remaining groups leaving at intervals of two minutes.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The distance raced was 318 kilometres (198 mi), with South African Rudolph Lewis winning the gold medal in the individual race.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Frederick Grubb of Great Britain won the silver medal, and Carl Schutte of the United States won the bronze.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] However, the average positions of the Swedish team were better than their competitors', and so the Swedish team won the gold medal for the team competition.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The silver and bronze medals followed the individual victories, going to Great Britain and the United States respectively – giving Grubb and Schutte a second medal each of the same varieties.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] All of the medals in the men's competitions were split between the diving teams of the Sweden and Germany.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The men's high dive was a Swedish white out, with Swedish divers taking all three medal positions.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Erik Adlerz took the gold medal, and proceeded to take the gold medal for Sweden in the 10 metre platform too.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Albert Zürner took the silver for Germany, and Gustaf Blomgren won the bronze medal for Sweden.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Another white out occurred in the 3 metre springboard with all three medals going to the German team, with Paul Günther taking gold, Hans Luber in the silver medal position and Kurt Behrens in bronze.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] A 10-metre platform event also took place for women, with Sweden taking two more medals, Greta Johansson in gold and Lisa Regnell in silver.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain's Isabelle White won the bronze medal.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The remaining finalists were all from Sweden.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Equestrian made its first appearance at a modern Olympics in the 1912 Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Although competitions involving horse riding had been included in the programme of 1900, this was the first appearance of modern Olympic staples such as dressage, eventing and show jumping.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] It was expected that the competitors would be military personnel as they would have had the cavalry experience to compete.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was split between the military competitions, prize riding and prize jumping.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] In the military competition, seven countries put forward competitors for the individual and team eventing.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Each nation put forward four athletes with the exception of Denmark, which only put forward three.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Some of the countries also nominated reserves in addition to their main athletes.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The total length of the course was 55 kilometres (34 mi) with the start and finish both in the grounds of the Field Riding Club.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The heat was such on the day of the event that competitors lost as much as 4.5 pounds (2.0 kg) in weight.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Swede Axel Nordlander won the individual competition, and led the Swedish eventing team to victory as well, earning himself two gold medals.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] In second place in the individual competition was German Friedrich von Rochow, who also earned a second silver medal as the team from Germany placed second overall.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Only the bronze medals were split up between nationalities, with the American team including Guy Vernor Henry, Jr. taking the bronze for the team event, while Frenchman Jacques Cariou won the individual medal.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Two additional countries entered for the dressage, although only Sweden entered the maximum number of competitors.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The event resulted in Sweden taking all three medals, with the gold going to Carl Bonde, the silver to Gustaf Adolf Boltenstern and the bronze to Hans von Blixen-Finecke.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The team event saw Sweden take another gold medal, with the French team second and the German team, featuring Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia, in the bronze medal position.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The foil competition became a full Olympic event, having appeared at the 1908 Games as a demonstration sport.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Nedo Nadi and Pietro Speciale of Italy took the gold and silver medals respectively, and Richard Verderber of Austria placed third.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] There were individual and team events in both épée and sabre.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The épée team event saw Belgium take the gold medal and Great Britain and the Netherlands in second and third place respectively.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] A member of the Belgian team went on to take the individual title as well, with Paul Anspach taking the gold medal.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Ivan Joseph Martin Osiier of Denmark took the silver medal, and another Belgian who was not in the team event, Philippe le Hardy de Beaulieu, won the bronze medal.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The sabre competition was dominated by the competitors from Hungary, with their team taking the gold medal over Austria and the Netherlands.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The individual competition saw a shut out by Hungarian athletes with Jenő Fuchs winning the overall competition, Béla Békessy in second and Ervin Mészáros in third.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Thirteen countries signalled their intention to enter football teams for the 1912 Olympics.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] A standard cup tie system was implemented, with the final deciding the gold and silver medallists and a third/fourth position playoff deciding the bronze medal winner.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Only FIFA affiliated teams were allowed to take part, with the public draw for the tournament taking place on 18 June 1911.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The tournament itself started on 29 June.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] In the first round Finland defeated Italy 3–2, Austria beat Germany 5–1 and the Netherlands emerged victorious over Sweden 4–3.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The team from Great Britain, who had won the gold medal at the 1908 Summer Games, were given a bye to the second round, where they faced Hungary and won 7–0.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Finland also won their match, defeating Russia 2–1.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Denmark matched the British scoreline, winning 7–0 against Norway, and the Netherlands won against Austria 3–1.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The semi final matches pitted Great Britain against Finland, where they won 4–0, and Denmark against the Netherlands, ending in a 4–1 victory for Denmark.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Netherlands won the third/fourth place playoff by the biggest scoreline of the tournament, beating Finland 9–0.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Later on the same day the final was played in the Olympic Stadium, where Great Britain retained its gold medal against Denmark in front of 25,000 spectators.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Goals from Harold Walden, Arthur Berry and two from Gordon Hoare helped Britain to win by a margin of 4–2.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The gymnastic competition at the 1912 Games featured a single individual competition and three team events in addition to a variety of displays by the various teams.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish team naturally won the Gymnastics event of the Swedish system, referred to in the programme as "Team Competition I", with fellow Scandinavian teams Denmark and Norway taking the second and third positions.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The all around team competition came second, with Italy taking the gold.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, one of the Italian team members, Alberto Braglia, won the individual gold for the same event.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Louis Ségura of the French team won the individual silver, while another member of the Italian team, Adolfo Tunesi, won the individual bronze.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The all around team competition saw Hungary take the silver medal and the team from Great Britain in third place.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The final team competition allowed for a free choice of movements and apparatus.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] This was another all Scandinavian affair, with the Norwegian team emerging victorious, Finland in second and Denmark in the bronze medal position.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Modern pentathlon was competed for at the 1912 Games, marking its first appearance in the Olympics.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] It was for these games that the five events of shooting, swimming, equestrian, fencing and cross country running were decided to make up the pentathlon.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was spread out across five days from 7 through to 12 July, ending with the cross country race.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Only men participated in the event, although a woman named Helen Preece was briefly enrolled to compete until the organizing committee ultimately denied her entry.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] For the shooting element, each competitor was allowed to bring their own pistol.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The shooting part of the competition was won by Gösta Åsbrink, with Georg de Laval and Gösta Lilliehöök in second and third place respectively, all three representing Sweden.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The swimming event was three lengths, each of 100 metres (330 ft), with the athletes split into eight heats and times going forward to calculate positions.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Ralph Clilverd of Great Britain won this event, with Edmond Bernhardt of Austria in second and de Laval in third.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The fencing competition saw each competitor face off against each other.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Several opponents were noted for their particular skill in the event with Åke Grönhagen of Sweden coming first with 24 wins, Jean de Mas Latrie of France second with 23, Sidney Stranne of Sweden in third with 21 and Patton of the United States close behind with 20.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Thirteen of the competitors cleared the equestrian course without any penalties, with Grönhagen winning the event, Bror Mannström of Sweden in second and de Laval third.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The cross country run was over 4,000 metres and started in the Olympic Stadium itself.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The event was run as a time trial with competitors leaving one minute apart.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] As this was the final event, the winning competitors were announced after the race, with Lilliehöök winning the gold medal, Åsbrink taking silver and de Laval, bronze.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The highest placed non-Swedish competitor was Patton, who finished fifth.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The rowing events at the 1912 Olympics did not prove popular with the public.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] This was put down to the "fatigue" of the public due to the volume of sporting events.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The eight competition was split into heats, with two teams in each heat.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The two British crews were lucky not to be drawn against each other, with the team from Leander Club facing New College, Oxford in the final.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Leander won by a length with a time of 6:15.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The coxed four followed a similar format to the eights, with the German team from Ludwigshafener Ruderverein defeating Britain's Thames Rowing Club in the final.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The competition for the coxed four, inriggers was much smaller, with only four nations competing.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Danish team defeated Sweden in the final.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The single sculls heats proved controversial with the first round race between Mart Kuusik and Alfred Heinrich being re-run after a protest by Heinrich.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, Cecil McVilly was disqualified in the first round after colliding with the boat of Martin Stahnke.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Wally Kinnear of Great Britain defeated Polydore Veirman of Belgium in the final, with Kinnear winning the matchup easily.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The yachts for the sailing competition assembled at Nynäshamn on 19 July, along with the other vessels that were to take part in an Olympic regatta.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The racing itself started the following day with the 12 metre class.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] There were only three nations and yachts competing in this event, the hosts Sweden, as well as Norway and Finland.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Norway won the gold medal, Sweden the silver and Finland came in last place, winning bronze.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The 10 metre class had the same number of countries entering it, although this time Sweden entered two yachts and Russia competed instead of Norway.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish yacht *Kitty* was the winning vessel, with the Finnish boat in second and the Russians coming third.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] A slightly improved field was featured in the 8 metre class, with four countries entering two yachts each.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The medals were awarded to exactly the same nations as the 12 metre class, another all Scandinavian affair.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The 6 metre class saw the most diverse field of any of the sailing events at the 1912 Olympics: six countries entered a total of nine yachts.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] France and Denmark competed in their only sailing event, along with Sweden, sending two yachts each.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Those three nations were the successful in the event, with the French yacht *Mac Miche* taking the gold, the Danish *Nurdug II* taking silver and the Swedish *Kerstin* placing third.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] There were eighteen shooting events at the 1912 Olympics, of which eight were team events.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was split predominantly into three sections: military rifle shooting, shooting with miniature rifles, pistols and revolvers, and clay bird and running deer shooting.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish and American competitors were the most successful at the competition, with seven gold medals each, although Sweden won a total of seventeen medals while the United States team won fourteen.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] 64-year-old Oscar Swahn, part of the Swedish single shot running deer team, is still the oldest gold medal winner in Olympic history.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] In swimming, Hawaiian Duke Kahanamoku won the 100 metre freestyle for the United States, who also saw Harry Hebner win gold in the 100 metre backstroke.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Canadian team also took two gold medals, both by George Hodgson in the 400 and 1,500 metre events.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The German swimming team won all three medals in the 200 metre breaststroke, with the gold going to Walter Bathe, who won a further gold in the 400 metre breaststroke.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Australasian team was victorious in the men's relay, with the United States finishing in the silver medal position and Great Britain placing third.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The 1912 Games saw the implementation of swimming events for women, with the 100 metre freestyle and 400 metre team relay taking place.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Fanny Durack won the individual contest, breaking the world record for the distance in the fourth heat.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Her fellow Australian Mina Wylie won the silver medal, and Jennie Fletcher of Great Britain came third to take the bronze medal.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The British team had further success in the women's relay, winning the team relay with the German team in second place and the Austrian team in third.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Because only four countries entered the relay there were no heats; only a final was held.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The United States did not field a women's team.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] New Olympic Records were set in all swimming events at the 1912 Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Tennis on covered courts was agreed initially for the 1912 Games, with competitions run for gentlemen's singles and doubles, ladies' singles, and mixed doubles.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The outdoor tournament was confirmed once the Östermalm Athletic Grounds were completed in late 1911, with the plans modified to have both indoor and outdoor tournaments.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Six countries sent players for the covered court competitions, with representatives from Sweden, Great Britain, Denmark, France, Australasia, and Bohemia appearing.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Included in this lineup was Australasia's only competitor, Anthony Wilding from New Zealand, who was also the reigning Wimbledon gentlemen's champion.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The indoor knockout competition started on 5 May, and continued as expected until the semi-final round where Wilding was beaten by Britain's Charles P.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The British player met Frenchman André Gobert in the final, but Gobert was victorious over the Englishman in straight sets.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Wilding took the bronze medal in a playoff against another British player, Arthur Lowe.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The outdoors tennis competition saw 70 players enter from 12 nations.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] However, Great Britain did not enter any competitors as the dates of the outdoor competition clashed with the 1912 Wimbledon Championships, despite attempts by the British authorities to convince the Olympic organizing committee to change the dates.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Other noted tennis players refused to compete at the Olympics and instead attended Wimbledon.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The gold and silver medals in the gentlemen's singles ended up being decided between two South Africans, with Charles Winslow and Harold Kitson playing each other.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The duo also competed as a pair in the gentlemen's doubles and took the gold medal, beating the Austrians Felix Pipes and Arthur Zborzil.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Marguerite Broquedis of France defeated Dorothea Koring of Germany in the ladies' singles for the gold medal.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] In the mixed doubles Koring teamed up with Heinrich Schomburgk to win the gold, the duo defeating Sigrid Fick and Gunnar Setterwall of Sweden in the final.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The tug of war competition was scheduled to take place between 7 and 12 July, with two matches taking place each day.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] However, out of the five countries which elected to enter the competition, only two actually appeared.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain arrived for its match against Bohemia, but the opposition team was nowhere to be found.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The same thing happened once more for the second match, with the Swedish team, made up of policemen from Stockholm, arriving to find that the Austrian team had not arrived.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden was announced as the winners of the match in the Austrians' absence.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] On the second day of the competition, Great Britain took on Sweden, the only occasion where both teams actually turned up for the bout.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The British team were made up of the winners of the gold medal in the same event at the 1908 Games, with the exception of John Sewell and Mathias Hynes.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] As the British team also consisted of policemen, the bout ended up effectively being between the City of London Police and the Stockholm Police, with the Swedish team winning 2–0.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Due to the non-appearance of the team from Luxembourg, that one match ended up being the entire tug of war event at the 1912 Olympics.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden was awarded the gold medal and Great Britain the silver.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The water polo tournament was set up on a modified elimination system as there were six teams entered.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The first round saw the British team defeating the Belgian team, Sweden defeating the French team and Austria defeating Hungary.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Lots were drawn to determine which match would take place in the second round as there were three teams left in the competition.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain were drawn to face Sweden, who they defeated.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Austria automatically qualified for the final against the winner of the Britain-Sweden matchup.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain won the gold medal in the event, defeating Austria 8–0.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Playoff matches were then played between each pair of defeated teams in order to decide the second and third places.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden and Belgium played off after a further three matches to decide the silver and bronze medal positions, with Sweden emerging victorious 4–2.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The nations at the 1912 Games entered a total of 267 wrestlers, although the actual competitors who appeared in Sweden were fewer, with 171 actually turning up to compete.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Greco-Roman wrestling was the only style of wrestling competed for at the Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The bouts took place in the open air in an area of the Olympic stadium, with the wrestlers split according to weight into five divisions: featherweight, lightweight, middleweight A (later referred to as middleweight), middleweight B (later referred to as light heavyweight) and heavyweight.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The skills of the competitors from Finland were noted in the featherweight competition, with Kaarlo Koskelo taking the gold medal, while German Georg Gerstäcker took silver and a further medal went to Finland with Otto Lasanen taking bronze.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The lightweight class drew the most attention from the public, with Emil Väre winning gold after beating all of his opponents by pin rather than by points.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Swedish wrestlers Gustaf Malmström and Edvin Mattiasson took the silver and bronze medals respectively.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Claes Johanson won Sweden's only gold medal in the middleweight competition, with his fellow finalist from Russia, Martin Klein, retiring before fighting Johanson in the final.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] This was due to the semi-final match between Klein and Alfred Asikainen of Finland lasting 11 hours and forty minutes, although they took breaks for refreshments every half-hour.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Klein was awarded the silver medal and Asikainen the bronze.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The light heavyweight competition saw another marathon length match, with the bout between Anders Ahlgren of Sweden and Ivar Böhling of Finland for the gold medal lasting more than nine hours.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The match was then declared a draw with both athletes being awarded the silver medal as neither won the match.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The bronze medal went to Hungary's Béla Varga, who was defeated by Ahlgren in the semi-final match.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Yrjö Saarela of Finland was victorious in the heavyweight competition after having placed second in the light heavyweight event at the 1908 Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Johan Olin took another medal for Finland with the silver and Søren Marinus Jensen repeated his bronze medal at the 1908 Olympics with another for Denmark.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The 1912 Summer Olympics saw the introduction of art competitions at the Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Events were implemented for literature, sculpture, painting, architecture and music.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Walter Winans won the gold medal for his sculpture, *An American Trotter*, which added to his previous gold medal for the running deer (double shot) competition at the 1908 Olympics and the silver medal in the running deer competition in 1912.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Baron Pierre de Coubertin, President of the IOC and founder of the modern Olympic movement, won the gold medal for literature.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] He actually entered the competition under the pseudonyms of Georges Hohrod and Martin Eschbach from Germany.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] With the exception of the sculpture competition, only gold medals were issued.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Italian Riccardo Barthelemy won the medal for music with his *Olympic Triumphal March*, and fellow countryman Giovanni Pellegrini won the gold for painting.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Swiss architects Eugène-Edouard Monod and Alphonse Laverrière shared the gold for their stadium design.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The sole silver medal, for sculpture, went to Frenchman Georges Dubois for his *Model of the entrance to a modern stadium*.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] In the evening of 7 July, demonstrations took place in the Olympic Stadium of sports from the Swedish island of Gotland.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] These began at 7:30pm with a demonstration of Pärk, a type of tennis with seven players a side.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] At the same time, at the other end of the stadium, a type of Icelandic wrestling called Glima was demonstrated.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Once those displays had concluded, further demonstrations were made of the Swedish sport varpa, similar to quoits, and stångstörtning, a version of the caber toss.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The three disciplines showcased were pärk, varpa and stångstörtning.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Baseball was also demonstrated at the Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] A game was played between the United States, the nation where the game was developed, and Sweden, the host nation.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The game was held on Monday, 15 July 1912 and started at 10 a.m. on the Ostermalm Athletic Grounds in Stockholm.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The Americans were represented by various members of the American Olympic track and field athletics delegation, while the Swedish team was the Vesterås Baseball Club, which had been formed in 1910 as the first baseball club in Sweden.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Four of the Americans played for Sweden, as the Swedish pitchers and catchers were inexperienced.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] One Swede eventually relieved Adams and Nelson, the American pitchers.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Six innings were played, with the Americans not batting in the sixth and allowing the Swedes to have six outs in their half of the inning.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The game was umpired by George Wright, a retired American National League baseball player.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Twenty-eight nations competed at the 1912 Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Egypt participated for the first time, as did Luxembourg, Iceland, Portugal, and Serbia.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Japan also made their Olympic debut, marking the first appearance of an Asian country at an Olympic Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Chile made its first appearance as a national team, with fourteen athletes attending the Games, although it had previously entered one individual at the 1896 Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] This was also the first time that athletes from Armenia had competed in the Olympics, as part of the team from Turkey (the officially recognised name for the Ottoman Empire).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Serbia's appearance was the only time it attended an Olympic Games as an independent nation until the 2008 Summer Olympics, almost one hundred years later.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The only nation that participated in the previous games in London 1908 but was absent in Stockholm 1912 was Argentina.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Austria and Hungary competed as two sovereign countries.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality they were two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] At the time, Australasia (Australia and New Zealand), Canada and South Africa were all part of the British Empire.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Egypt was de jure under the control of Turkey, but had been de facto run by the British since 1882.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] This was the last Olympics that allowed "private entries", i.e. individual athletes that were not part of a country's officially selected team.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] Arnold Jackson was one such private entry; he won the 1500 metres by 0.1 seconds, ahead of an American trio, in what was acclaimed at the time to be "the greatest race ever run".
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] His medal is still credited to the United Kingdom, however.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] These are the top 10 nations that won medals at the 1912 Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1912-summer-olympics] The medals themselves included solid gold medals, the last time these were given out.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1928-summer-olympics-national-flag-bearers] During the opening ceremony of the 1928 Summer Olympics, athletes from each country participating in the Olympics paraded into the arena.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1928-summer-olympics-national-flag-bearers] As Olympic tradition dictates, most participating nations paraded in the alphabetical order of the language of the host country (here Dutch), except Greece, who enters first at the founding nation of the Olympics, and the host country (here the Netherlands) who enters last.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1928-summer-olympics-national-flag-bearers] During the Parade of Nations, athletes from all participating countries entered the Olympisch Stadion.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1928-summer-olympics-national-flag-bearers] Each team was led by a flag bearer that was one of their athletes or officials, designated either by their respective National Olympic Committee (NOC) or by the athletes themselves.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1928-summer-olympics-national-flag-bearers] Below is a list of parading countries and their announced flag bearer, in the same order as the parade.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1928-summer-olympics-national-flag-bearers] This is sortable by country name, flag bearer's name, or flag bearer's sport.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1928-summer-olympics-national-flag-bearers] Names are given in the form officially designated by the IOC (International Olympic Committee).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1952-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] During the Parade of Nations section of the 1952 Summer Olympics opening ceremony, athletes from each country participating in the Olympics paraded into the arena.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1952-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The Parade of Nations was organized according to the Finnish name of the country.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1952-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Greece led the parade followed by the Netherlands Antilles.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1952-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Other countries marched by following the Finnish alphabet, except the host country, Finland, which marched last.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1952-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The athletes from British Guiana and the People's Republic of China were absent from the Parade of Nations, meaning only 67 nations participated in the parade.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1964-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] During the Parade of Nations portion of the 1964 Summer Olympics opening ceremony, athletes from each country participating in the Olympics paraded in the arena, preceded by their flag.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1964-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The flag was borne by a sportsperson from that country chosen either by the National Olympic Committee or by the athletes themselves to represent their country.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1964-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Although the Games were held in Japan, English was used to organize the Parade of Nations instead of Japanese.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1964-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Had the parade followed the Japanese characters, Greece would have been followed by Iceland, and Rhodesia would have been the penultimate country before Japan.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1964-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The Japanese language order would not be introduced until 2020 when the country hosted the games for the fourth time.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] During the Parade of Nations section of the 1972 Summer Olympics opening ceremony, athletes from each country participating in the Olympics paraded in the arena, preceded by their flag.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] As the nation of the first modern Olympic Games, Greece entered the stadium first; whereas, the host nation West Germany marched last, according with tradition and IOC guidelines.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Announcers in the stadium read off the names of the marching nations in the host country's language, German, by actor and television personality Joachim Fuchsberger and music during the parade of nations is composed by Kurt Edelhagen.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Whilst most countries entered under their short names, a few entered under acronym or alternative names, mostly due to political and naming disputes.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] 121 nations entered the stadium with a combined total of 7,134 athletes.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Eleven nations made their Olympic debut, namely Albania, Dahomey (now Benin), Gabon, North Korea, Lesotho, Malawi, Saudi Arabia, Somalia, Swaziland, Togo, Upper Volta (now Burkina Faso).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Rhodesia's invitation to take part in the 1972 Summer Games was withdrawn by the International Olympic Committee four days before the opening ceremony, in response to African countries' (such as Ethiopia and Kenya) protests against the Rhodesian government.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] (Rhodesia did, however, compete in the 1972 Summer Paralympics, held a little earlier in Heidelberg.) Rhodesian athletes would have been marched between Republic of China and Romania.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The following is a list of each country's announced flag bearer.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The list is sorted by the order in which each nation appears in the parade of nations.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The names are given in their official designations by the IOC.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1972-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] This table is sortable by country name (in German), the flag bearer's name, and the flag bearer's sport.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] During the parade of nations section of the 1976 Summer Olympics opening ceremony, athletes from each country participating in the Olympics paraded in the arena, preceded by their flag.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The flag was borne by a sportsperson from their respective country chosen either by the National Olympic Committee or by the athletes themselves to represent their country.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] As the nation of the first modern Olympic Games, Greece entered the stadium first; whereas, the host nation Canada marched last, in accordance with the tradition and IOC guidelines.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] As each delegation entered accompanied by the music to be composed by Vic Vogel, the national name was announced in French and English (the official languages of the Olympics).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Whilst most countries entered under their short names, a few entered under acronyms or alternative names, mostly due to political and naming disputes.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] West Germany (Federal Republic of Germany) entered as **A**llemagne (*République Federal de Allemagne*), East Germany (German Democratic Republic) as **R**épublique Démocratique Allemande, North Korea (Democratic People's Republic of Korea) as **R**.P.D.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Corée (*République Populaire Démocratique de Corée*), and Soviet Union (Union of Soviet Socialist Republics) as **U**.R.S.S.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] (*Union des Républiques Socialistes Soviétiques*).
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Ninety-two nations entered the stadium with a combined total of 6,084 athletes.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Four of them made their Olympic debut, namely Andorra (which had its overall Olympic debut a few months before in Innsbruck), Antigua and Barbuda (as *Antigua*), Cayman Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Because of the 1976 Summer Olympics boycott, several African countries which marched at the parade eventually withdrew from the Games, including Cameroon, Morocco, and Tunisia.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Senegal and Ivory Coast were the only African countries that competed throughout the duration of the Games.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Elsewhere, Burma, Iraq and Guyana also opted to join the Congolese-led boycott.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Other countries, such as El Salvador and Zaire, did not participate in Montreal for purely economic reasons.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/1976-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] This table is sortable by country name (in French), the flag bearer's name, and the flag bearer's sport.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Announcers in the stadium read off the names of the marching nations in French, English, (the official languages of the Olympics) and Mandarin Chinese with music accompanying the athletes as they marched into the stadium.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The Marshall Islands, Montenegro, and Tuvalu debuted at these Games, and Serbia competed under its name for the first time after the 1912 Summer Olympics.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Montenegro and Serbia were previously one country as the State Union of Serbia and Montenegro.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Per tradition, Greece entered first as the spiritual home of the Olympic Games, and the host country, China, entered last.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] All nations in between marched in the order of their names in Chinese, the host country's language.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] As Chinese does not have an alphabetical order, the National Olympic Committees were sorted based on stroke count in Simplified Chinese characters.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Brunei (文莱) was excluded from the Games by the IOC shortly before the Opening Ceremony as no athletes had been registered.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] One of the published lists of flag bearers was later edited to note this.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] Brunei athletes would have originally marched 36th between Uzbekistan and Barbados.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The following is a list of each country's flag bearer.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The list is sorted by the sequence that each nation appeared in the parade of nations.
[src:2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations/2008-summer-olympics-parade-of-nations] The names are given in their official designations by the IOC, and the Chinese names follow their official designations by the Beijing Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games.
